        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our goal is to map the clump G331.372-00.116 at sufficient sensitivity, angular resolution, and spectral resolution to measure its internal structure and determine the core mass function and the kinematics of the cores (veloities, line widths, and profiles). The best compromise between continuum and line sensitivity, and the availability of suitable molecular lines, occurs at frequencies near 270 GHz.

Sensitivity: 

We require sufficient sensitivity to detect cores down to ~0.2 Msun. For cold dust ~15K, a 0.2 Msun core will have a 267 GHz flux of 0.4 mJy at the 5 kpc distance of our source.

From MALT90, we know the brightness temperatures of density-tracing species like HCO+ and HNC (1-0) are T_B = 0.5 K level in a 38" beam. Since the densities are high, especially toward the cores, the 1 mm lines are likely to be comparable. In fact, they are likely to be brighter, since the single-dish emission is almost certainly beam-diluted, and the cores will have high-densities, above the critical densities. Moreover, in cold, dense clouds the ground state 1-0 transitions are often self-absorbed. The 1 mm lines, therefore, are likely to be brighter than 0.5 K. Indeed, excitation models suggest that for conservative values of the abundances, the core brightness temperatures will be several K. As a conservative sensitivity estimate, and since optically thin transitions are typically a few times fainter than the main isotopic lines, we require ~0.05 K for our 1 sigma line sensitivity in order to detect them. This sensitivity will provide a SNR of ~15 for 0.5 K lines, which is required in order to measure line profiles accurately to search for infall signatures. 

The bandwidth selected will provide good spectral resolution to detect any profile signatures in the line selected.

This setup will achieve point-source sensitivities in the continuum of 0.06 mJy, yielding 7 sigma detections for 0.2 Msun cores. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We allocate 11 spectral windows in dual polarization mode (bandwidth of 234 MHz and 468 MHz) and position them to cover several key molecular transitions. Since the single-dish line widths are typically ~4 km/s, to accurately measure the velocities, line widths, and line profiles, we require a velocity resolution of ~0.5 km/s. For the highest priority transitions, therefore, we select a resolution of 0.5 km/s. Setting all the spectra windows with this resolution produces a data rate higher that 12 Mb/s. In order to prevent this, we use a spectral averaging of 4 in 6 of the spectral windows that covered other transitions of interest.

Since we are uncertain as to the range of densities and temperatures, it is important to choose lines that span a range of excitation energies and optical depths. A critical diagnostic is to choose an optically thick line and its much optically thinner isotopologue, since chemical effects are minimized and the relative optical depths are well constrained by isotopic abundance ratios. We have therefore chose a set-up that contains the required optically thick transitions (HCO+ 3-2 and HNC 3-2), as well as the optically thin isotopologue HC18O+ 3-2. The optically thick lines will be our primary lines to measure velocities and line widths. We also selected the deuterated molecule NH2D, which is expected to be bright and well detected in the very cold cores, and a good tracer of the cold dense gas (e.g., Sanhueza et al. 2013). Although unexpected, warm gas, if present, will be probed by including a few high-excitation energy or shock-tracing lines of CH3OH, H2CS, SO2 and HC3N. This spectral setup will result in a aggregate bandwidth of 3.75 GHz, more than sufficient to detect the continuum emission with high sensitivity.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We require sufficient angular resolution to resolve the size scale of individual cores (~0.05 pc). For a distance of 5 kpc, the required angular resolution is 2". Our simulations of ALMA observations show that this is adequate to measure the core mass function reliably above 1 Msun from crowded fields, and above 0.2 Msun for well separated cores.

To cover the extent of the clump requires a 12-point mosaic (see Fig. 4 for the coverage and mosaic positions). To address our science goals of detecting the large-scale continuum and line emission from the clump as a whole also requires the inclusion of the ACA. From our previous ALMA observations of G0.253_0.016, we have found that the inclusion of large-scale emission is critical to reliably trace the large-scale dust continuum and gas motions.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
